<h2>HVAC Systems in Alabama</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Alabama's humid subtropical climate places heavy demands on HVAC systems, particularly during the long cooling season that typically extends from April through October. Summer temperatures regularly reach the upper 80s to mid-90s Fahrenheit, with high humidity levels that make efficient air conditioning essential for comfort. The state's mild winters, with average temperatures ranging from the 40s to 60s, require minimal heating, making heat pumps an excellent choice for year-round climate control as they provide both efficient cooling and heating capabilities.</p>

<p>For optimal performance in Alabama's climate, HVAC systems should have a minimum SEER (Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio) rating of 16, with SEER 18-20 systems providing the best long-term value for homeowners with high cooling loads. The high humidity levels throughout much of the year make proper dehumidification crucial, requiring systems with variable-speed components and appropriate sizing to maintain comfort while controlling moisture. Ductwork design and insulation are particularly important in Alabama, as poorly insulated ducts in hot attics can significantly reduce system efficiency and increase energy costs.</p>

